b"Meaning that after a year with the ostomy bag, he had the reconstructive surgery, so no more bag and he is doing great.  I'm so sorry you are so ill. b"Pfizer   My cancer story 
My life has proven to be a journey of unexpected challenges. I was diagnosed with a rare form of cancer (Rhabdomysarcoma) at 3 years old. I was cancer-free a year after my diagnosis, but left with permanent ostomy (colostomy and urostomy),for rest of my life. Through my journey, faith in God, support from family & friends I am bless to have my desires, passions, and dreams come true. I have been a fashion model for over 17 years, yes with my ostomy bags. To see the outer appearance no one could ever tell I live with these adversities. 
Today at 49 years old I am helping other cancer survivors, ostomy patients, youth mentoring groups, women's health organizations, and those suffering with low self-esteem. I do not look like what I deal with 24 hours/7 days a week. I am not suppose to! Living my life to make difference in the cancer community 
Jearlean Taylor

b'The clinical signs of neuropathic pain (central impairment, peripheral impairment, or both) are identical even though the lesions may initially belong to different lesions.
The lack of awareness of these pains by patients as well as by doctors is one of the gateways to chronic pain.
The treatment of neuropathic pain is mainly the treatment of the pathology of the first disease.
The exclusive treatment against neuropathic pain (neglecting the treatment of initial lesions) is a palliative treatment. There is very little or no cure of this symptomatology.
The central connections between the fibers of the emotions and the networks of the fibers of nociception require psychological care and the acquisition of psychological techniques to cope.'

b'Donations???\nI am a Staten Island resident my whole life. Fortunately, i live in an area of the Island practically unaffected by HUrricane Sandy. Others, like those that live in New Dorp Beach, were not as lucky. Myself and many families from Mid Island Little League drove in a caravan of trucks full of water,snacks,prepared foods,sandwiches,candy,soda,gatorade and much more. The men set up grills and barbecued hamburgers and hot dogs for the people of New Dorp who lost everything and for the sanitation workers working hard down there. The only thing we saw FEMA do was stick "CONDEMNED" signs on peoples doors. What frightened me the most was many elderly telling me they lost all their medications. As a RN, I know the imminent danger in that. You can not abruptly stop certain meds. If nothing else is done, these people need help immediately. PLEASE get it out there, on TV or wherever, these folks need serious help in Staten ISland.\nThank you, Jackie Kaffl, proud Staten Islander'

b'MONTREAL \xe2\x80\x94 Pharmaceutical giant Pfizer has announced it's cutting about 300 jobs across Canada, most of them in Montreal.

Julie-Catherine Racine, a spokesman for Pfizer Canada, said Sunday that the cuts will be spread across several locations but the majority will be at the company's headquarters in the Montreal suburb of Kirkland.

"After an extensive and rigorous review of our organizational structure and of the competencies required for the future, I can confirm that Pfizer in Canada has undergone a restructuring in various parts of its Canadian business," Racine said in a statement.

In total, about 11 per cent of the company's total Canadian workforce will be eliminated, she said.

The company recently completed a $31.7-million upgrade to its Montreal manufacturing and distribution centre. The Quebec government contributed $2.7 million to that project.

Pfizer employs 2,700 people across Canada, including 1,800 in Quebec.'
